// NCE — Part 2 (Q31-120)
var _qs = window.QUESTIONS_DATA["nce"] || (window.QUESTIONS_DATA["nce"] = []);

_qs.push(
{id:"nce-31",q:"Which of the following BEST describes the ACA ethical principle of 'autonomy'?",options:["Doing what's best for the client","Respecting the client's right to self-determination and choice","Maintaining confidentiality","Being honest with the client"],answer:1,explanation:"Autonomy = respecting the client's right to self-determination and choice. It means providing information, supporting informed decisions, and not imposing the counselor's values. Tensions arise when autonomy conflicts with beneficence (e.g., suicidal clients, mandatory treatment)."},
{id:"nce-32",q:"Which of the following BEST describes the ACA ethical principle of 'fidelity'?",options:["Honesty","Keeping promises and honoring the trust placed in the counselor","Doing no harm","Confidentiality"],answer:1,explanation:"Fidelity = keeping promises and honoring the trust in the professional relationship. Includes following through on commitments, maintaining clear professional boundaries, and being trustworthy. Related to beneficence and the therapeutic relationship."},
{id:"nce-33",q:"Which of the following BEST describes the ACA ethical principle of 'justice'?",options:["Being fair","Treating all clients fairly and ensuring equitable access to counseling services","Honesty","Confidentiality"],answer:1,explanation:"Justice = treating all clients fairly and working to ensure equitable access to counseling services. Includes non-discrimination, advocating for underserved populations, and addressing systemic barriers. Connected to multicultural and social justice competence."},
{id:"nce-34",q:"Which of the following BEST describes the ACA ethical principle of 'veracity'?",options:["Loyalty","Truthfulness and honesty in dealings with clients and others","Confidentiality","Doing no harm"],answer:1,explanation:"Veracity = truthfulness. Counselors are honest with clients, colleagues, supervisors, and the public. Avoiding deception in advertising, billing, and professional communications. Endorse the qualifications of others honestly."},
{id:"nce-35",q:"Which of the following BEST describes the difference between 'ethics' and 'law' in counseling?",options:["They are identical","Ethics are professional standards; laws are legally binding mandates — they overlap but can differ","Ethics come from the law","Laws are voluntary"],answer:1,explanation:"Ethics (ACA Code) are professional standards established by the profession. Laws are legally binding mandates from government. They overlap (e.g., mandated reporting is both ethical and legal) but can differ (e.g., confidentiality scope, scope of practice). Counselors follow the higher standard when in conflict."},
{id:"nce-36",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'dual relationships'?",options:["Working with two clients","Being in two distinct roles with a client (e.g., counselor + business partner) — potentially harmful","A normal therapeutic tool","Required by ethics"],answer:1,explanation:"Dual (multiple) relationships occur when the counselor is in two distinct roles with a client. Examples: social, business, romantic, familial. The ACA Code prohibits when risk of harm; some non-harmful dual relationships are permissible (e.g., attending a client's public event). Always consult supervision. Sexual/intimate dual relationships are never ethical."},
{id:"nce-37",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'sexual intimacy' between counselor and client?",options:["Allowed after termination","Strictly prohibited at all times","Allowed if both consent","A gray area"],answer:1,explanation:"Sexual intimacy (any sexualized conduct, not just intercourse) with a current client is strictly prohibited by the ACA Code and is illegal in most states (often a felony). Sexual contact within 5 years of termination is also prohibited; after 5 years, the burden of proof is on the counselor to show no exploitation."},
{id:"nce-38",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'bartering' with clients?",options:["Always prohibited","Generally discouraged; permitted only when non-exploitive, culturally appropriate, and the client benefits","Always allowed","Required for low-income clients"],answer:1,explanation:"The ACA Code: bartering is generally discouraged due to the risk of exploitation and boundary issues. It may be appropriate in some cultural contexts or when it benefits the client. Must be documented carefully. Cannot establish an exploitative relationship."},
{id:"nce-39",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'gifts' from clients?",options:["Always prohibited","Discouraged; evaluate for therapeutic intent, value, and risk of boundary violation","Always required","A tax deduction"],answer:1,explanation:"Gifts are evaluated case by case. Consider: the value, the therapeutic intent, the cultural context, the risk of altering the relationship, the message it sends. Decline large/personal gifts. Small tokens of appreciation from children or in some cultural contexts may be acceptable. Document. Consult supervision."},
{id:"nce-40",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'termination' in counseling?",options:["A legal process","The planned, collaborative ending of the therapeutic relationship (avoids abandonment)","Always sudden","Required after 10 sessions"],answer:1,explanation:"Termination is the planned, collaborative ending. Discussed from intake. Includes: client readiness, treatment goals met, mutually agreed time, referrals if needed, handling of records, and a chance to process the ending. Avoids abandonment (which is unethical). Important therapeutic work happens in the ending."},
{id:"nce-41",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'abandonment' in counseling?",options:["Planned termination","Unilaterally ending the relationship without proper referral or notice","Termination by mutual agreement","A type of CBT"],answer:1,explanation:"Abandonment = ending services without providing reasonable notice, alternatives, or referral. Different from termination (planned and collaborative). Unethical. Examples: counselor quits practice without notice, doesn't return calls during crisis. Always provide reasonable notice and referral."},
{id:"nce-42",q:"Which of the following BEST describes the 'counselor wellness' ethical imperative?",options:["Optional self-care","Counselors have an ethical obligation to monitor their own well-being and seek help when needed","A luxury","Required only for new counselors"],answer:1,explanation:"The ACA Code requires counselors to monitor their own well-being and seek professional help when needed. Counselors with unresolved personal issues that could affect client care should seek supervision, counseling, and/or time off. Self-care is an ethical obligation, not a luxury."},
{id:"nce-43",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'burnout' in counselors?",options:["Normal fatigue","A state of physical, emotional, and mental exhaustion from chronic workplace stress, often leading to reduced efficacy and compassion fatigue","A diagnosis","A type of therapy"],answer:1,explanation:"Burnout: physical, emotional, and mental exhaustion from chronic stress. Symptoms: cynicism, detachment, reduced efficacy, exhaustion, compassion fatigue. Common in helping professions. Prevention: self-care, supervision, balanced caseload, boundaries, time off. Counselor wellness is an ethical obligation."},
{id:"nce-44",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'compassion fatigue'?",options:["Burnout","The cost of caring for those in distress; symptoms similar to PTSD (re-experiencing, avoidance, arousal) from empathic engagement with traumatized clients","A type of personality disorder","A coping skill"],answer:1,explanation:"Compassion fatigue (Figley): the cost of caring. Symptoms: intrusive thoughts, avoidance, arousal, exhaustion, depression, reduced empathy. Common in trauma work. Distinct from burnout (emotional exhaustion) and secondary traumatic stress (PTSD-like from client trauma exposure). Self-care, supervision, and limiting exposure help."},
{id:"nce-45",q:"Which of the following BEST describes the 'Counselor Self-Disclosure' ethical standard?",options:["Required for rapport","Discouraged except when it serves a clear therapeutic purpose and is in the client's best interest","A right of the client","Always prohibited"],answer:1,explanation:"Self-disclosure is generally discouraged, but allowed when it serves a therapeutic purpose (e.g., normalizing experiences, building rapport, providing hope, modeling). Must be in the client's best interest, brief, and not shift focus to the counselor. Avoid self-disclosure for the counselor's own needs."},
{id:"nce-46",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'HIPAA' as it applies to counseling?",options:["A code of ethics","A US federal law that protects the privacy and security of health information, including mental health records","A state law only","A test for counselors"],answer:1,explanation:"HIPAA (1996) is a US federal law. The Privacy Rule protects PHI (Protected Health Information). The Security Rule covers electronic PHI. Includes: notice of privacy practices, patient rights, minimum necessary, business associate agreements. Some states have stricter laws — counselors follow the higher standard."},
{id:"nce-47",q:"Which of the following BEST describes the HIPAA 'minimum necessary' rule?",options:["Share as much as possible","Disclose only the minimum amount of PHI necessary to accomplish the purpose","Always share with insurance","A type of therapy"],answer:1,explanation:"The minimum necessary standard: when using, disclosing, or requesting PHI, use/disclose/request only the minimum necessary. Exceptions: treatment, disclosure to the client, authorized by the client, required by law. Documentation should be appropriate. Don't over-share with insurance or family."},
{id:"nce-48",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'FERPA'?",options:["A federal law protecting the privacy of student education records (K-12 and higher ed)","A state law for HIPAA","A code of ethics","A test for counselors"],answer:0,explanation:"FERPA (1974) is a US federal law. Protects the privacy of student education records. Applies to all schools receiving federal funds. Parents have rights until 18 (or post-secondary); then rights transfer to the student. School counselors are governed by FERPA (not HIPAA). Confidentiality has exceptions (e.g., safety, court order)."},
{id:"nce-49",q:"Which of the following BEST describes a 'mandated reporter'?",options:["A journalist","A professional who is required by law to report suspected abuse/neglect of children, elders, or dependent adults","A type of therapist","A federal agent"],answer:1,explanation:"Mandated reporters (counselors, teachers, doctors, nurses, social workers) are required by law to report suspected abuse/neglect. Most states: child abuse, elder abuse, dependent adult abuse. Some states also include domestic violence. Report typically to CPS or APS. Failure to report is a crime in most jurisdictions."},
{id:"ncece-50",q:"Which of the following BEST describes the scope of mandated reporting?",options:["Only when you witness","Reasonable suspicion of abuse or neglect — you don't need proof, but you do need a legitimate reason to suspect","Only confirmed cases","Only with parent's consent"],answer:1,explanation:"Mandated reporters must report when they have reasonable suspicion. You don't need proof; you need a legitimate reason based on facts. The investigation is the agency's job. Failure to report because you weren't sure is a violation. When in doubt, report. Immunity typically provided for good-faith reports."},
{id:"nce-51",q:"Which of the following BEST describes a 'tele-counseling' consideration?",options:["Same as in-person","Unique considerations: licensure in the client's state, secure platforms, informed consent for distance services, technology competence","No ethics apply","No special considerations"],answer:1,explanation:"Tele-counseling has unique considerations: licensure (must be licensed in the client's state unless using interstate compacts), technology (secure, encrypted platforms, no public Wi-Fi), informed consent (additional risks, emergency plan, technology failures), and competence (training in telehealth)."},
{id:"nce-52",q:"Which of the following BEST describes the 'PSYPACT' or interstate counseling compacts?",options:["A federal law for counselors","Interstate compacts that allow licensed counselors to practice across participating states (e.g., ASWB for social work, PSYPACT for psychology)","A type of certification","A type of insurance"],answer:1,explanation:"The Counseling Compact (and similar compacts for other professions) allows licensed professional counselors to practice across participating member states without obtaining a separate license. It includes specific requirements (e.g., 3 years of practice, no disciplinary history). Check current state participation."},
{id:"nce-53",q:"Which of the following BEST describes the 'Group work' ethical standard?",options:["Same as individual","Special considerations: confidentiality within the group, screening members, informed consent about group limits, handling conflicts, termination","No consent needed","Always required"],answer:1,explanation:"Group work has special considerations: informed consent (including limits of confidentiality in group), screening members for appropriateness, defining group norms, handling conflicts and rule-breaking, dealing with member attrition, preparing members for termination. Confidentiality in groups is more complex than in individual work."},
{id:"nce-54",q:"Which of the following BEST describes the 'Family counseling' ethical consideration regarding minors?",options:["Parents always have access","Confidentiality with minors is complex: legal rights vary by state and age; balance minors' developing autonomy with parental rights and best interests","Minors have no rights","Always require parental consent"],answer:1,explanation:"Counseling minors is complex: many states allow minors to consent for certain services (e.g., substance abuse, mental health, sexual health). Confidentiality may be limited by parents' rights. Best practice: discuss confidentiality with both parents and child at intake, balance the minor's developing autonomy and best interests with parental involvement."},
{id:"nce-55",q:"Which of the following BEST describes the 'ACA Code' position on technology/social media?",options:["Discouraged","Not addressed","Counselors must maintain professional boundaries, ensure client privacy, and obtain informed consent for any technology use","Required"],answer:1,explanation:"The ACA Code addresses technology: online counseling, social media boundaries, electronic records, encryption, informed consent for technology. Key principles: client privacy and confidentiality, professional boundaries, competence in technology, separation of professional and personal online presence."},
{id:"nce-56",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'multicultural counseling'?",options:["Knowing facts about cultures","An integrative approach that recognizes sociocultural context in clients' lives and uses culturally appropriate intervention strategies (Sue, Ivey, Pedersen)","A type of medication","A test"],answer:1,explanation:"Multicultural counseling recognizes the importance of sociocultural context. Key theorists: Derald Wing Sue (multicultural counseling competencies), Allen Ivey (micro-counseling, cross-cultural), Paul Pedersen (multiculturalism as a fourth force). MSJCC: attitudes/beliefs, knowledge, skills, and action. Don't pathologize cultural difference."},
{id:"nce-57",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'racial/cultural identity development' (Cross, Helms, Sue)?",options:["A linear process","A non-linear, multi-stage model of how individuals develop awareness and understanding of their own and others' cultural identities","A single stage","A medical model"],answer:1,explanation:"Racial/cultural identity development is non-linear. Models: Cross (Black identity development), Helms (White identity development), Sue (multicultural), Hardiman & Jackson. Stages range from unawareness to integration/positive identity. Counselor self-awareness of their own identity is foundational."},
{id:"nce-58",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'microaggressions'?",options:["Major acts of discrimination","Brief, everyday verbal, behavioral, or environmental indignities (intentional or unintentional) that communicate hostile, derogatory, or negative racial slights","A legal term","A diagnostic category"],answer:1,explanation:"Microaggressions (Sue et al., 2007): brief, everyday exchanges that send denigrating messages. Three forms: microassault (explicit), microinsult (subtle rudeness), microinvalidation (exclusion, dismissal). Often unintentional by the perpetrator but harmful in cumulative impact. Important to address and avoid."},
{id:"nce-59",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'White Fragility' (Robin DiAngelo)?",options:["A diagnosis","A state in which even a minimum amount of racial stress becomes intolerable, triggering defensive moves to restore equilibrium","A physical injury","A therapy technique"],answer:1,explanation:"White Fragility (DiAngelo): the defensive reaction white people have when their racial worldview, biases, or advantages are challenged. Manifests as argumentation, silence, tears, guilt, or denial. The book's purpose is to encourage self-reflection and growth, not to assign blame."},
{id:"nce-60",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'cultural humility' (Tervalon & Murray-García)?",options:["Knowing all cultures","A lifelong process of self-reflection and self-critique to address power imbalances and develop mutually beneficial partnerships with communities","A certification","A medical approach"],answer:1,explanation:"Cultural humility (Tervalon & Murray-García, 1998): a lifelong process of self-reflection, self-critique, and learning. Three components: lifelong learning, self-awareness of assumptions and biases, and developing mutually beneficial partnerships with communities. Differs from cultural competence (which can imply an endpoint)."},
{id:"nce-61",q:"Which of the following BEST describes the ACA's stance on LGBTQ+ clients?",options:["Conversion therapy is acceptable","Affirming stance; conversion therapy is unethical and harmful; counselors support clients' sexual orientation and gender identity","Neutral","Discourages advocacy"],answer:1,explanation:"The ACA opposes conversion/reparative therapy (it is harmful and ineffective). Counselors affirm diverse sexual orientations and gender identities. They advocate for LGBTQ+ clients' rights, address heterosexism and cissexism, use affirming language and documentation, and provide competent care including support for coming out, transitioning, and family/relationship work."},
{id:"nce-62",q:"Which of the following BEST describes the difference between 'sexual orientation' and 'gender identity'?",options:["Same thing","Sexual orientation = who one is attracted to; gender identity = one's internal sense of being male, female, both, or neither","A medical distinction","A legal term"],answer:1,explanation:"Sexual orientation = emotional, romantic, and/or sexual attraction (gay, lesbian, bisexual, queer, asexual, etc.). Gender identity = one's internal sense of gender (man, woman, nonbinary, genderqueer, etc.). They are distinct. Gender expression = how one presents (masculine, feminine, androgynous). Sex assigned at birth ≠ gender identity."},
{id:"nce-63",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'affirmative therapy' for transgender clients?",options:["Conversion therapy","An approach that affirms the client's gender identity, supports social/medical transition if desired, and addresses minority stress","A medical treatment","A test"],answer:1,explanation:"Affirmative therapy for trans clients: affirms gender identity, supports exploration of identity and transition if desired, addresses minority stress (discrimination, family rejection, internalized transphobia), advocates for clients' rights, coordinates care with medical providers (hormone therapy, surgery) when appropriate. WPATH SOC provides standards of care."},
{id:"nce-64",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'intersectionality' (Crenshaw)?",options:["A road","The interconnected nature of social categorizations (race, gender, class, sexuality, etc.) that create overlapping systems of discrimination or disadvantage","A diagnosis","A therapy technique"],answer:1,explanation:"Intersectionality (Crenshaw, 1989): the interconnected nature of social categorizations (race, gender, class, sexuality, ability, etc.) that create overlapping systems of discrimination or disadvantage. Counselors recognize that clients hold multiple identities, and the intersections shape their lived experience in unique ways."},
{id:"nce-65",q:"Which of the following BEST describes the 'biopsychosocial' model in counseling?",options:["Bio only","A holistic model that considers biological, psychological, and social/cultural factors in understanding and treating clients","Psycho only","A medical model only"],answer:1,explanation:"Biopsychosocial (Engel, 1977): holistic perspective. Biological (genetics, neurochemistry, medical conditions), psychological (thoughts, emotions, behaviors, history), social/cultural (environment, relationships, culture, systems). The standard in counseling and medicine. Compare to purely biomedical model."},
{id:"nce-66",q:"Which of the following BEST describes the 'medical model' of mental illness?",options:["Holistic","A perspective that views mental disorders as diseases with biological causes, treated with medication and other biological interventions","Sociocultural","A community model"],answer:1,explanation:"The medical model views mental disorders as diseases with biological causes (genes, brain chemistry, pathology) and is treated primarily with medication and biological interventions. Compare to biopsychosocial (more holistic), recovery model (client empowerment, hope), and community models (social, environmental)."},
{id:"nce-67",q:"Which of the following BEST describes the 'recovery model' in mental health?",options:["Cure-focused","A strengths-based, person-centered approach that emphasizes hope, empowerment, choice, and community integration, even with ongoing symptoms","Medication-focused","A medical model"],answer:1,explanation:"The recovery model (SAMHSA, Anthony): hope, personal responsibility, education, self-advocacy, support. Recovery is a process, not an endpoint. It emphasizes strengths, empowerment, choice, peer support, and community integration. Applicable even with ongoing symptoms. Foundations in consumer/survivor movement."},
{id:"nce-68",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'evidence-based practice' (EBP) in counseling?",options:["Practice based on intuition","The integration of best available research with clinical expertise and client values/context","Practice based on the latest theory","Practice based on a single study"],answer:1,explanation:"EBP = integration of: (1) best available research, (2) clinical expertise (counselor's skill, judgment), and (3) client characteristics, values, and context. The APA (2006) tripartite model. EBP ≠ practice based on a single study. Counselors must use empirical evidence thoughtfully, not as the sole basis."},
{id:"nce-69",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'outcome research' in counseling?",options:["Research about therapy outcomes","Quantitative research measuring the effectiveness of specific therapies (often RCTs) for specific disorders","A type of personality test","A test for counselors"],answer:1,explanation:"Outcome research = quantitative studies of whether therapy works (typically RCTs). Process research = how therapy works. Common findings: therapy works (the 'dodo bird verdict' that all approaches are roughly equal in effectiveness), the therapeutic relationship is the strongest predictor, some approaches are better for specific problems."},
{id:"nce-70",q:"Which of the following BEST describes the 'common factors' theory (Rosenzweig, Frank)?",options:["A type of medication","The idea that factors common to all therapies (therapeutic relationship, expectations, hope, structure) account for much of therapy's effectiveness","A type of CBT","A diagnostic test"],answer:1,explanation:"Common factors theory: the elements shared across all effective therapies account for much of their benefit. Includes: the therapeutic relationship/working alliance, expectations of success (placebo), hope, a healing ritual/setting, therapist warmth/empathy, client factors. As important as technique. The 'dodo bird' verdict."},
{id:"nce-71",q:"Which of the following BEST describes the 'working alliance' (Bordin)?",options:["A business contract","The bond between therapist and client, with three components: goals, tasks, and bond","A legal document","A type of CBT"],answer:1,explanation:"The working alliance (Bordin, 1979) has three components: Goal agreement (mutual agreement on therapy goals), Task agreement (agreement on the methods), and Bond (the affective connection). The strongest predictor of therapy outcome across modalities. Built early; ruptures are common and useful to address."},
{id:"nce-72",q:"Which of the following BEST describes a 'rupture' in the therapeutic alliance?",options:["A type of break","A breakdown in the collaborative bond between therapist and client (avoidance, conflict, or strain)","A legal concept","A termination"],answer:1,explanation:"A rupture (Safran & Muran) is a deterioration in the therapeutic alliance. Manifests as: withdrawal/avoidance (client doesn't engage), or confrontation/conflict (anger, disagreement). Ruptures are NORMAL and, if addressed, can lead to deeper alliance and better outcomes. Avoid the 'rupture trap' (pretending nothing happened)."},
{id:"nce-73",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'active listening' (Carl Rogers)?",options:["Listening while taking notes","Listening with full attention, empathy, and non-judgment, while also reflecting back content, feelings, and meaning","Listening to multiple clients","A test-taking strategy"],answer:1,explanation:"Active listening (Rogers, Carkhuff) involves: paying full attention, withholding judgment, reflecting content, paraphrasing, summarizing, reflecting feelings, and reflecting meaning/depth. Empathic, accurate understanding. Core skill for all theoretical orientations. Often practiced via micro-counseling (Ivey)."},
{id:"nce-74",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'empathy' in counseling?",options:["Sympathy","The ability to understand the client's internal frame of reference and to communicate that understanding","Feeling sorry for the client","Sharing your own experience"],answer:1,explanation:"Empathy = accurate understanding of the client's internal frame of reference and the ability to communicate that understanding. Different from sympathy (feeling for the client) and compassion (wanting to help). Rogers: empathy is one of three core conditions. Strong predictor of therapy outcome."},
{id:"nce-75",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'unconditional positive regard' (Rogers)?",options:["Always agreeing","Non-judgmental acceptance and warmth toward the client, regardless of what the client says or does","Liking everything about the client","Praising the client"],answer:1,explanation:"UPR (Rogers) = non-possessive, non-judgmental acceptance and warmth. Not the same as unconditional approval of behavior (counselors can challenge harmful behaviors) or always agreeing. The client feels safe to explore without fear of judgment. The other two core conditions: empathy and congruence."},
{id:"nce-76",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'congruence' (Rogers)?",options:["Being perfect","The counselor being genuine, authentic, and transparent in the relationship","Always telling the truth","Following the rules"],answer:1,explanation:"Congruence (Rogers) = genuineness, authenticity, transparency. The counselor's inner experience matches their outer expression. Doesn't mean disclosing everything; it means being real rather than hiding behind a professional facade. The third core condition for therapeutic change (with empathy and UPR)."},
{id:"nce-77",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'concreteness' in counseling?",options:["A personality trait","A skill of being specific and definite in communication (concrete examples, specific behaviors) rather than abstract or vague","A type of CBT","A diagnostic test"],answer:1,explanation:"Concreteness (Carkhuff) is a core skill: being specific, definite, and clear. Avoiding abstract, vague, or general statements. Examples: 'When did it happen?' 'What did you say?' 'How did you feel?' Helps clients move from vague feelings to specific, actionable understanding."},
{id:"nce-78",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'immediacy' in counseling?",options:["Quick action","A skill of addressing the here-and-now of the therapeutic relationship in the session","A type of crisis intervention","A test"],answer:1,explanation:"Immediacy = bringing the therapeutic process into the here-and-now, often by discussing the client-counselor relationship. Example: 'I notice you hesitated when I asked about your family.' Or 'How is it for you to share this with me?' Strengthens the alliance and models relational honesty."},
{id:"nce-79",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'confrontation' in counseling?",options:["Anger","A skill of challenging discrepancies, defenses, or blind spots in a supportive way","Aggression","A legal process"],answer:1,explanation:"Confrontation (challenging) = pointing out discrepancies between what a client says and does, contradictions, avoidance, or blind spots. Distinct from aggression. Should be empathic, timely, and at the client's pace. Use with skill and care. Connects to CBT Socratic questioning and psychodynamic interpretation."},
{id:"nce-80",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'paraphrasing' in counseling?",options:["Repeating verbatim","Restating the client's message in the counselor's own words to demonstrate understanding","Asking a question","A type of intervention"],answer:1,explanation:"Paraphrasing = restating the client's message in the counselor's own words, briefly and accurately. Demonstrates active listening and understanding. Different from reflection of feeling (which focuses on emotion) and summarization (which combines themes). Core attending and listening skill."},
{id:"nce-81",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'reflection of feeling' in counseling?",options:["Mirroring","Identifying and reflecting the client's underlying emotion to demonstrate empathic understanding","Asking about feelings","A test"],answer:1,explanation:"Reflection of feeling = naming or reflecting the client's emotion to deepen understanding. Examples: 'You feel hurt when your partner dismisses you.' Goes beyond paraphrase (content) to the emotional layer. Skill of accurate empathy. Use carefully — don't over-interpret or project."},
{id:"nce-82",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'summarizing' in counseling?",options:["Brief summary of a session","Linking multiple themes, content, or feelings from a session or sessions to provide cohesion and meaning","A test","A type of note"],answer:1,explanation:"Summarizing = pulling together multiple themes, content, or feelings to provide cohesion. Used at transitions: end of session, start of next session, transitions in topic. Helps the client see patterns. Part of active listening and case formulation."},
{id:"nce-83",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'open-ended questions' in counseling?",options:["Yes/no questions","Questions that can't be answered with a single word, encouraging exploration and elaboration","Closed questions","Test questions"],answer:1,explanation:"Open-ended questions: 'How did that make you feel?' 'What was that like?' 'Tell me more about...'. Encourage exploration, elaboration, narrative. Compare to closed questions (yes/no, single-word). Best practice: balance both; overuse of either can be problematic."},
{id:"nce-84",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'closed questions' in counseling?",options:["Open-ended questions","Questions that can be answered briefly (yes/no, single word, specific fact)","Test questions","A type of homework"],answer:1,explanation:"Closed questions: 'Did you sleep last night?' 'When did it start?' Useful for: clarifying, gathering facts, narrowing, assessing risk. Best practice: balance with open-ended questions. Overuse can feel like an interrogation."},
{id:"nce-85",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'Socratic questioning' in CBT?",options:["Lecturing","A method of guided discovery using systematic questions to help clients examine their thoughts and arrive at new perspectives","A personality test","A test"],answer:1,explanation:"Socratic questioning (Beck, Ellis) is a collaborative method of guided discovery. Types: clarification ('What do you mean?'), assumptions ('What are you assuming?'), evidence ('What evidence supports that?'), perspective ('How would others see it?'), implications ('What's the consequence?'), questions about the question. Used in CBT and many other modalities."},
{id:"nce-86",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'cognitive distortions' (Beck)?",options:["Mental illness","Systematic errors in thinking that maintain negative beliefs and emotions (e.g., all-or-nothing, catastrophizing, mind reading)","A type of personality disorder","Normal thinking"],answer:1,explanation:"Cognitive distortions (Beck) are systematic errors in thinking. Common ones: all-or-nothing thinking, overgeneralization, mental filter, discounting the positive, jumping to conclusions (mind reading, fortune telling), catastrophizing, emotional reasoning, should statements, labeling, personalization. Targeted in CBT through cognitive restructuring."},
{id:"nce-87",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'automatic thoughts' (Beck)?",options:["Reflexes","Brief, situation-specific cognitions that occur without deliberation, often with strong emotional impact","A type of personality trait","A medical symptom"],answer:1,explanation:"Automatic thoughts (Beck) are rapid, involuntary thoughts that arise in response to situations. They often contain cognitive distortions. The CBT model: situation → automatic thought → emotion → behavior. Clients learn to identify, evaluate, and restructure these thoughts. Often recorded in thought records."},
{id:"nce-88",q:"Which of the following BEST describes a 'thought record' in CBT?",options:["A legal document","A structured worksheet where clients record situations, thoughts, feelings, behaviors, and alternative interpretations","A type of note","A diagnostic tool"],answer:1,explanation:"A thought record (Beck) is a core CBT tool. Columns: situation, automatic thought, emotion (with intensity 0-100), cognitive distortion, evidence for/against, balanced thought, emotion after. Used to identify patterns, evaluate evidence, and develop balanced thinking. Often assigned as homework."},
{id:"nce-89",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'behavioral activation' (BA) in depression treatment?",options:["A test","A CBT technique: scheduling activities that bring pleasure or mastery to counteract withdrawal and negative mood","A medication","A diagnostic tool"],answer:1,explanation:"Behavioral activation (Lewinsohn, Jacobson, Martell) targets the depression cycle: low mood → avoidance → less reward → worse mood. Schedule: pleasant activities, mastery experiences, values-aligned action. Often used in CBT and as a standalone treatment for depression. Strong evidence base."},
{id:"nce-90",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'exposure therapy' for anxiety?",options:["Avoidance","A CBT/behavioral therapy technique: graduated, repeated exposure to feared stimuli to reduce fear through habituation and extinction","A type of medication","A test"],answer:1,explanation:"Exposure therapy: graduated, prolonged, repeated exposure to feared stimuli. Mechanisms: habituation, extinction, new learning. Types: in vivo (real life), imaginal, in virtuo (VR), interoceptive. Used for phobias, OCD, PTSD (prolonged exposure), panic. Often combined with response prevention (for OCD) or cognitive restructuring."},
{id:"nce-91",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'mindfulness' in counseling?",options:["A religious practice","Non-judgmental present-moment awareness; a skill central to DBT, ACT, MBCT, and other third-wave therapies","A medical treatment","A test"],answer:1,explanation:"Mindfulness (Kabat-Zinn): non-judgmental, present-moment attention. Cultivated in MBSR, MBCT, DBT, ACT, and many other approaches. Benefits: emotion regulation, reduced rumination, increased self-awareness. Practices: breath awareness, body scan, mindful movement. Foundational to many evidence-based approaches."},
{id:"nce-92",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'Acceptance and Commitment Therapy' (ACT)?",options:["A type of medication","A third-wave CBT that uses acceptance, mindfulness, and values-based action to increase psychological flexibility","A personality test","A diagnostic tool"],answer:1,explanation:"ACT (Hayes) is a third-wave CBT. The hexaflex: acceptance, cognitive defusion, present-moment awareness, self-as-context, values, committed action. Goal: psychological flexibility. The model is that suffering comes from avoidance, not from thoughts/feelings. 'The struggle switches.' Strong for anxiety, depression, chronic pain."},
{id:"nce-93",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'Motivational Interviewing' (MI)?",options:["A confrontational approach","A collaborative, goal-oriented counseling style that helps clients resolve ambivalence about change by eliciting their own motivations","A diagnosis","A test"],answer:1,explanation:"MI (Miller & Rollnick) is collaborative, evocative, and honoring of autonomy. Used to resolve ambivalence and elicit change talk. Four processes: engaging, focusing, evoking, planning. OARS skills: open questions, affirmations, reflections, summaries. Originally for substance use, now widely applied."},
{id:"nce-94",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'change talk' in MI?",options:["A diagnosis","The client's own arguments for change (desire, ability, reason, need, commitment)","A type of CBT","A test"],answer:1,explanation:"Change talk = the client's own language about change. Types: desire, ability, reason, need (DARN) and commitment, activation, taking steps (CAT). Sustain talk = language favoring the status quo. MI counselors elicit, reinforce, and shape change talk. The 'language of change' is predictive of actual change."},
{id:"nce-95",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'sustain talk' in MI?",options:["Talk about changing","The client's arguments for keeping things the same (status quo)","A type of CBT","A test"],answer:1,explanation:"Sustain talk = the client's own language favoring the status quo, reasons not to change, ambivalence. Normal and expected. MI counselors don't argue against it (which would trigger discord). They reflect and then guide the client to consider change. Elicit change talk, evoke it, roll with resistance."},
{id:"nce-96",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'developing discrepancy' in MI?",options:["A diagnosis","A core MI technique: helping the client see the gap between their current behavior and their broader goals/values","A test","A medication"],answer:1,explanation:"Developing discrepancy (Miller & Rollnick): helping the client see how current behavior conflicts with their values, goals, or future vision. The client, not the counselor, should make the case for change. Avoid being the one to argue for change (creates resistance). The discrepancy is the motivation."},
{id:"nce-97",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'rolling with resistance' in MI?",options:["Avoiding resistance","An MI principle: rather than opposing or confronting resistance, the counselor acknowledges and redirects it, sometimes with strategic reflection","A type of medication","A test"],answer:1,explanation:"Rolling with resistance (MI): rather than confronting (which increases resistance), the counselor rolls with it. Reflect it, reframe, shift focus, or amplify (carefully). Don't push too hard. The client needs to perceive autonomy. Resistance is a signal to change strategy."},
{id:"nce-98",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'confrontation' in MI?",options:["A core technique","Not a core technique; MI emphasizes collaboration, evocation, autonomy/choice","A medical procedure","A test"],answer:1,explanation:"MI explicitly avoids confrontation as a primary strategy. The spirit of MI: collaboration, evocation (drawing out, not pouring in), autonomy/choice, compassion, acceptance. Confrontation is more typical of older, less effective approaches. Roll with resistance, elicit change talk, evoke the client's own motivations."},
{id:"nce-99",q:"Which of the following BEST describes the 'Stages of Change' (Prochaska & DiClemente)?",options:["A diagnosis","Precontemplation, Contemplation, Preparation, Action, Maintenance (and sometimes Relapse) — the Transtheoretical Model","A type of therapy","A test"],answer:1,explanation:"TTM (Prochaska & DiClemente): PC, C, P, A, M, and sometimes Relapse. Used in MI matching. Precontemplation = no intention to change; Contemplation = ambivalent; Preparation = planning; Action = actively changing; Maintenance = sustaining; Relapse = return. Different interventions match each stage."},
{id:"nce-100",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'precontemplation' in the Stages of Change?",options:["Active change","Not yet considering change; may be unaware or in denial; resistant to interventions about the issue","Planning","Maintenance"],answer:1,explanation:"Precontemplation: not intending to take action in the foreseeable future (next 6 months). May be unaware, uninformed, or demoralized. Interventions: raise awareness, provide information, plant seeds. Pushing for action increases resistance. The client must see the issue first."},
{id:"nce-101",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'contemplation' in the Stages of Change?",options:["Active change","Aware of the problem and seriously thinking about change, but ambivalent (next 6 months)","Planning","Maintenance"],answer:1,explanation:"Contemplation: intending to change in the next 6 months. Aware of the pros of changing and the cons of staying the same — ambivalent. Interventions: explore ambivalence, evoke change talk, develop discrepancy, support self-efficacy. May remain in this stage for years (chronic contemplation)."},
{id:"nce-102",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'preparation' in the Stages of Change?",options:["Active change","Intending to take action soon (next month); making a plan; may have taken some small steps","In maintenance","Precontemplation"],answer:1,explanation:"Preparation: intending to take action within the next month. Typically has a plan of action and may have taken some small steps. Interventions: help the plan be specific, identify barriers and supports, build self-efficacy. Best moment for action-oriented interventions."},
{id:"nce-103",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'action' in the Stages of Change?",options:["Planning","Active modification of behavior; requires considerable commitment of time and energy","Contemplation","Maintenance"],answer:1,explanation:"Action: has made specific overt modifications in lifestyle within the past 6 months. Highest risk of relapse. Interventions: support, problem-solving, skill-building, addressing barriers, relapse prevention. Action is visible; earlier stages are not."},
{id:"nce-104",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'maintenance' in the Stages of Change?",options:["Active change","Working to consolidate gains and prevent relapse; typically 6 months to 5 years after action","Precontemplation","Contemplation"],answer:1,explanation:"Maintenance: has been working to prevent relapse; typically 6 months to 5 years after action (after that, often considered termination/healthy behavior). Interventions: relapse prevention, support, occasional check-ins, lifestyle integration. The longest stage."},
{id:"nce-105",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'relapse' in the Stages of Change?",options:["Linear progression","Return to old behaviors; common, often part of the process; not failure","Precontemplation","Always permanent"],answer:1,explanation:"Relapse: return to old behaviors. Common (most people relapse at some point). Not failure. View as learning opportunity. Re-enter the cycle. Interventions: identify triggers, build coping, normalize. Self-compassion helps. Don't shame or give up."},
{id:"nce-106",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'Lazarus' multimodal therapy (MMT)?",options:["A single theory","BASIC ID: a multimodal assessment across 7 dimensions (Behavior, Affect, Sensation, Imagery, Cognition, Interpersonal, Drugs/biology)","A medical model","A diagnosis"],answer:1,explanation:"Lazarus' BASIC ID: a comprehensive assessment across 7 dimensions. Behavior (actions, skills), Affect (emotions), Sensation (5 senses, somatic), Imagery (mental pictures, memories), Cognition (thoughts, beliefs), Interpersonal (relationships), Drugs/biology (substances, medical). Technical eclecticism — match interventions to the dimensions that need work."},
{id:"nce-107",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'technical eclecticism' (Lazarus)?",options:["Random technique selection","Selecting the best-fit techniques from various therapies based on client presentation and empirical support, without committing to one theory","A type of CBT","A type of family therapy"],answer:1,explanation:"Technical eclecticism (Lazarus): using techniques from any approach based on the client's needs and the evidence — not bound by a single theory's assumptions. Compare to theoretical integration (combining theories), assimilative integration (one primary theory with techniques from others), and common factors (relationship as the active ingredient)."},
{id:"nce-108",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'Gestalt therapy' (Perls)?",options:["A psychoanalytic approach","An existential/humanistic therapy focused on awareness, contact, and unfinished business in the here-and-now","A behavioral approach","A medication"],answer:1,explanation:"Gestalt therapy (Fritz Perls): existential, phenomenological, here-and-now. Key concepts: figure/formation, contact and contact boundary, unfinished business, polarities, the empty chair, awareness. The goal is to increase awareness, contact, and integration. Includes experiential techniques (e.g., two-chair, empty chair)."},
{id:"nce-109",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'unfinished business' in Gestalt therapy?",options:["A legal term","Unresolved emotional issues from the past that interfere with present functioning and prevent closure","A test","A diagnosis"],answer:1,explanation:"Unfinished business (Gestalt) = unresolved emotional issues (often grief, resentment, guilt, love) that interfere with present functioning. The empty chair technique: client talks to the absent person as if they were there. Resolution involves expressing the unexpressed and integrating. Can cause symptoms if not resolved."},
{id:"nce-110",q:"Which of the following BEST describes the 'empty chair' technique?",options:["A type of furniture","A Gestalt technique: client talks to an imagined person in the empty chair, expressing thoughts and feelings to complete unfinished business","A test","A medication"],answer:1,explanation:"The empty chair (Perls): a Gestalt technique. The client talks to an imagined person in the empty chair, expressing thoughts and feelings. Powerful for resolving unfinished business, integrating polarities, increasing awareness. Sometimes used with two chairs (alternating roles). Originally developed for grief, resentment, and relational issues."},
{id:"nce-111",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'Existential therapy' (Yalom, May, Frankl)?",options:["A behavioral approach","A therapy that focuses on the human condition — death, meaning, freedom, isolation, choice, and authentic living","A test","A medical treatment"],answer:1,explanation:"Existential therapy (Yalom, May, Frankl, Boss): focuses on the human condition. The four 'ultimate concerns' (Yalom): death, freedom (and its responsibility), isolation (existential), meaninglessness. Approach: authentic living, accepting limits, finding meaning, taking responsibility. Logotherapy (Frankl) emphasizes meaning through work, love, attitude."},
{id:"nce-112",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'logotherapy' (Frankl)?",options:["A behavioral therapy","An existential therapy that emphasizes finding meaning in life, even in suffering, through work, love, and attitude (Will to Meaning)","A medical treatment","A test"],answer:1,explanation:"Logotherapy (Frankl): 'Third Viennese School of Psychotherapy.' Meaning through: 1) creative (work, deeds), 2) experiential (love, beauty, truth), 3) attitudinal (meaning in unavoidable suffering). The 'Will to Meaning' is the primary human drive. Techniques: paradoxical intention, dereflection, Socratic dialogue."},
{id:"nce-113",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'narrative therapy' (White & Epston)?",options:["A medical approach","A post-structuralist therapy that views problems as separate from the client, uses 'externalizing' and re-authoring of life stories","A type of CBT","A test"],answer:1,explanation:"Narrative therapy (White & Epston): post-structuralist, social constructionist. Key concepts: problems are externalized (not the person), people's lives are multi-storied (some stories are dominant), unique outcomes are uncovered, re-authoring preferred stories. Documents like letters and certificates are common. The person is not the problem; the problem is the problem."},
{id:"nce-114",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'externalizing' in narrative therapy?",options:["Working outside","Separating the person from the problem ('the depression' rather than 'you are depressed') to reduce shame and open space for change","A type of family therapy","A diagnosis"],answer:1,explanation:"Externalizing (White): separating the person from the problem. 'The depression' rather than 'you are depressed.' Reduces shame, opens space for change, treats the problem as something to address rather than an identity. Clients explore how the problem has affected them and how they've resisted it."},
{id:"nce-115",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 're-authoring' in narrative therapy?",options:["Rewriting history","Helping the client develop new, preferred stories about their identity, relationships, and life","A test","A diagnosis"],answer:1,explanation:"Re-authoring: helping the client develop new, preferred stories. Identify 'unique outcomes' (moments when the problem didn't dominate) and amplify them. Connect to values, hopes, and skills. Often uses documents (letters, certificates, transcripts) to solidify the new story. A central narrative therapy process."},
{id:"nce-116",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'REBT' (Rational Emotive Behavior Therapy) (Ellis)?",options:["A psychoanalytic approach","A CBT precursor that focuses on the ABC model (Activating event, Belief, Consequence) and disputing irrational beliefs","A medication","A test"],answer:1,explanation:"REBT (Albert Ellis): the ABC model. A = Activating event. B = Belief (irrational). C = emotional Consequence. D = Disputation. E = Effect (new emotion). Irrational beliefs include: demandingness, awfulizing, low frustration tolerance, global evaluation. The goal: unconditional self-acceptance and other-acceptance."},
{id:"nce-117",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'irrational beliefs' (Ellis)?",options:["Beliefs held by irrational people","Rigid, dogmatic, absolutistic beliefs (e.g., 'I MUST be perfect') that lead to unhealthy negative emotions","A diagnosis","A type of medication"],answer:1,explanation:"Ellis's irrational beliefs: rigid, extreme, absolutistic (must, should, ought). Three main types: demandingness (I must be perfect), awfulizing (it's terrible), low frustration tolerance (I can't stand it). REBT disputes these into rational beliefs (preferences, flexible, can stand it). Goal: unconditional self-acceptance."},
{id:"nce-118",q:"Which of the following BEST describes the 'ABCDE' model in REBT?",options:["A type of test","Activating event, Belief, Consequence, Disputation, Effect — a model for identifying and disputing irrational beliefs","A medical model","A diagnostic tool"],answer:1,explanation:"ABCDE: A (Activating event), B (Belief), C (emotional Consequence), D (Disputation of irrational beliefs), E (Effect — new, healthier emotion). The intervention happens at D: identify the irrational belief, dispute it (logical, empirical, pragmatic). The new belief leads to a new emotion. Core REBT."},
{id:"nce-119",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'unconditional self-acceptance' (Ellis)?",options:["Always loving yourself","A philosophy where one's self-worth is not contingent on achievements, traits, or others' approval","A type of CBT","A diagnosis"],answer:1,explanation:"Unconditional self-acceptance (USA, Ellis): one's value as a person is not contingent on behavior, traits, achievements, or others' approval. You're worthwhile regardless. Contrast with conditional self-worth ('I'm only good if I succeed'). Related to self-compassion (Neff) and Rogers' UPR. Reduces shame and self-criticism."},
{id:"nce-120",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'self-compassion' (Neff)?",options:["Self-pity","Three components: self-kindness, common humanity, and mindfulness — treating oneself with warmth during difficulties","Selfishness","A diagnosis"],answer:1,explanation:"Self-compassion (Neff, 2003): three components — (1) self-kindness (vs. self-judgment), (2) common humanity (vs. isolation), (3) mindfulness (vs. over-identification). Treat yourself like a good friend would. Strong evidence base for reducing anxiety, depression, shame, and increasing well-being. Distinct from self-esteem."}
);
